issue.title: Improve Search Results
issue.body:
### Enter your suggestions in details:

Non-trivially often, I find that top search results on Google.com are random localized versions rather than the English version I'm looking for. I do _often_ get the right page, but sometimes it's really frustrating to have to figure out how to get the correct page in my language.

I do also worry about the impact of pages with very similar titles getting flagged as SEO juicing, but that might be a step beyond what's necessary to look at now.

I'm sure there are very well established guidelines for how to manage localized content and SEO, and my _guess_ is that we're not doing those but I'm not actually certain what they are - I do know quite a bit about SEO but I've never dealt with localization before.

issue.body: This PR allows `nodevu` to not break on non-node environments because it enforces undici. Whilst `undici` is awesome, by doing `await defaultFetch` (where defaultFetch is the undici import) it makes the library rent unusable on mixed server-client environments or on a pure client fashion.

issue.title: feat: add release date and modules version
issue.body:
Hi @bnb ,

Background:
We are currently consolidating the Node releases data logic/code in `nodejs/nodejs.org` repo (I am referencing this [PR](https://github.com/nodejs/nodejs.org/pull/5365)). And the repo has been using `nodevu` for some time. Then we found out that there are some fields that we need but not returned by `nodevu` yet.

We need these 2 new fields:
- `date` -> fetched from `index.json` and it's not the same with `support.phases.dates.start`. I am not too sure myself about the historical context behind it. However, it seems like: release date in `index.json` is referring to actual the release date and `support.phases.dates.start` is referring to the support start date ("current" status starts).
- `modules.version` -> fetched from `index.json` as well, see [this](https://nodejs.org/en/download/releases#backref-1) for explanation.

This PR is still in draft state (I haven't added any test or added to the docs), looking forward for your inputs/feedbacks.

issue.title: Use `engines` in modules where it is defined
issue.body:
There's a `package.json` property called `engines`. This property can be used for anything, but one of the few defined engines is `node`. It's extremely unfortunate that it's not been used in tooling like `fnm` yet, and would be incredible to see `fnm` adopt it as a version indicator.

The added complexity here will be around version ranges, since semver ranges are entirely within scope for this field.

Ideally, it would be _absolutely incredible_ if I could run `fnm` inside of a directory with the `engines` property defined and be presented with my options.

- Show a row for each acceptable release line
	- Prioritize the versions I've already got installed that match those releases
	- Show (via green/red text) if I don't have any versions installed that match the range and offer to install if I want to use that release line 

Engines documentation in the `npm-package.json` docs: https://docs.npmjs.com/files/package.json#engines

issue.title: Data Saver / Explicit Consent Mode
issue.body:
**Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.**

<!-- A clear and concise description of what the problem is. Ex. I'm always frustrated when [...] -->

I'm currently on an airplane and was scrolling the web app on my Mac. Refreshed the home page and at the top of the page was some pretty, uh, Classic Hellthread Content. I feel exceptionally bad for accidentally exposing the people around me to that and would love to see a way to ensure I (and others!) have complete control of what's shown when scrolling the Good Site.

**Describe the solution you'd like**

<!-- A clear and concise description of what you want to happen. -->

I'd specifically like to see a Settings toggle that forces all images behind the blurred image UI that I believe comes up on some content when you've got Content Filtering set to Warn. This would put all images behind the blured UI.

**Describe alternatives you've considered**

<!-- A clear and concise description of any alternative solutions or features you've considered. -->

- Not Using BlueSky in situations where seeing Classic Hellthread Content isn't appropriate
  - This is not a reasonable solution, as I have ADHD and will forget.
- Toggle to disable images altogether 
  - More aggressive for no benefit 
- Using filtering
  - Tried this, still saw Classic Hellthread Content. No OCR tools will ever be good enough to filter everything. 

**Additional context**
<!-- Add any other context or screenshots about the feature request here. -->
<3

I've gotten to dig in a bit now after fixing up my personal laptop setup. I do have one request here, would it be possible to name this `release` or `releaseDate` rather than `date`? My goal with this module is specifically to make it so the code can be a readable API without having to refer to docs or having to already have experience with `dist/index.json` or nodejs/release data. As such, IMO given the context you've provided here I think either of those names would be more clear.

```suggestion
    data[name].releases[`v${versionSemver.version}`].date = versions[version].release ?? undefined
```

```suggestion
    data[name].releases[`v${versionSemver.version}`].date = versions[version].releaseDate ?? undefined
```
